    The way we establish the identity of a sequence using DNA is called BLAST. When we do a BLAST search, we compare a sequence of nucleotides or amino acids to a database to search for significant matches. But what is a significant match? Does a certain percentage sequence identity mean two sequences are the “same”? In front of you, each pair has a 4-sided die. Decide which number will respresent A, C, G, and T. Each partner roll the die 20 times, writing down your DNA sequence as you go.

    But sequences are not random. You will share more sequence similarity with your siblings than you will with me. You’ll be more similar to me than a chimpanzee, and more similar to me and the chimpanzee than to a fish. When we’re doing identification, we need to be aware that there may be sequences that are closely related, but not exactly, our sequence. Additionally, it’s going to be far easier to match short sequences than long ones. This is dangerous for us in particular as viral genomes are often small. Our coronavirus sequence is 3000 base pairs. The human genome is 3.5 billion. You could fit the coronavirus genome over a million times into our genome. In a million tries, will there be some regions in our genome that look like coronavirus by chance? Yes.
